A pre-typing resolver runs as its own phase: AST in, name-resolved AST out, with every identifier bound to a definition site or flagged as unknown. This is the architecture in Rust (early-pass `Resolver`), Go (package-level resolution before typing), and most ML descendants.

An interleaved resolver runs name resolution and type checking together. This is required when:

- overload sets depend on the expected type (Java method overloading, C++ ADL, Swift overload resolution);
- extension methods or implicits add to the visible name set after types are known;
- dependent module paths (Scala `p.T`, OCaml `M.t`) make the meaning of a name depend on a value-level path;
- macro expansion changes the scope at the point of use, requiring scopes to be re-built incrementally.

The trade-off is diagnostic clarity versus expressive power: pre-typing resolution gives clean "unknown name" errors, while interleaved resolution can express overload-driven and type-directed lookup at the cost of more entangled error messages.
